  "prompt": "What do good piano hands look like?",
  "response": "Good piano hands typically have the following characteristics:\n\n1. Relaxed posture\n- Curved, natural hand shape\n- Relaxed wrists\n- No tension or stiffness\n\n2. Proper finger positioning\n- Rounded, slightly arched fingers\n- Fingers close to the keys\n- Fingertips used to press keys, not flat fingers\n\n3. Hand size and flexibility\n- Ability to span a comfortable range of keys\n- Flexibility and independent finger movement\n- Thumb positioned to easily reach keys\n\n4. Strong, independent finger control\n- Each finger can move independently\n- Ability to play smoothly and evenly\n- Good finger strength and dexterity\n\n5. Hand alignment\n- Hands parallel to the keyboard\n- Wrists level with keys\n- No twisting or awkward angles\n\n6. Hand span\n- Ability to reach intervals comfortably\n- Natural reach without stretching\n- Proportional hand size to keyboard\n\n7. Fluid movement\n- Smooth transitions between keys\n- Minimal unnecessary movement\n- Efficient, economic motion\n\nWhile these are general guidelines, hand anatomy varies, and pianists develop techniques that suit their individual physical characteristics.",
